The histogram above shows us that there are some traffic sign types where we have a very small sample size to train on. This means the model won't have a good chance to learn them. So make more of them...

If there are less than 500 images of a certain sign type in the test set:

  • Enlarge them with an affine transformation instead of just duplicating them, so there is variation
  • Add them back to the test set and add their labels back to the label set
In [6]:
# first, define the transformation matrix (M) for the affine transformation
offset = 3
startpoints = np.array([[offset,offset],[offset,31-offset],[31-offset,offset]]).astype(np.float32)
endpoints = np.array([[1,1],[1,31],[31,1]]).astype(np.float32)
M = cv2.getAffineTransform(startpoints,endpoints)

for i in range(1,n_classes):#+1):
    signindices = np.where(y_train==i)
    if (len(signindices[0]) < 500):
        #create a list of zeros to hold the added images. Using a numpy array gives errors from opencv operations later.
        addsigns = [[[ [0 for _ in range(3) ] for _ in range(32)] for _ in range(32)] for _ in range(len(signindices[0]))]
        addclassifier = []
        for j in range(len(signindices[0])):
            addsigns[j] = cv2.warpAffine(X_train_loaded[signindices[0][j]], M, (32,32))
            addclassifier.append(i)
        #X_train_loaded.append(addsigns)
        #y_train.append(addclassifier)
        X_train_loaded = np.append(X_train_loaded, addsigns, axis=0)
        y_train = np.append(y_train, addclassifier)
        
# Recalculate the number of training examples
n_train = X_train_loaded.shape[0]

# Check for mismatch between number of images and number of labels
assert X_train_loaded.shape[0] == y_train.shape[0]
assert X_valid_loaded.shape[0] == y_valid.shape[0]
assert X_test_loaded.shape[0] == y_test.shape[0]

Step 3: Design and Test a Model Architecture¶

Pre-process the data¶

Here I define several funtions that can be used to pre-process the data. This includes choosing a colorspace and normalizing the data between -1 and +1. It is interesting to see the difference in training the model depending on which function is used.

This function keeps all three channels of the RGB images. I found that it works the best of all these functions

In [11]:
def RGBnorm(X):
    rgbnorm = np.empty([X.shape[0],image_shape[0],image_shape[1],image_shape[2]],dtype=float)
    for n in range(0,X.shape[0]):
        for h in range(0,image_shape[0]):
            for w in range(0,image_shape[1]):
                rgbnorm[n][h][w][0] = (X[n][h][w][0]-128)/128
                rgbnorm[n][h][w][1] = (X[n][h][w][1]-128)/128
                rgbnorm[n][h][w][2] = (X[n][h][w][2]-128)/128
        
    return rgbnorm

This function converts the images to HSV color space.

In [12]:
def HSVnorm(X):
    hsvnorm = np.empty([X.shape[0],image_shape[0],image_shape[1],image_shape[2]],dtype=float)
    for n in range(0,X.shape[0]):
        hsvx= cv2.cvtColor(X[n],cv2.COLOR_RGB2HSV)
        hsvnormx = hsvx.astype(float)
        for h in range(0,image_shape[0]):
            for w in range(0,image_shape[1]):
                hsvnormx[h][w][0] = ((hsvx[h][w][0]-90)/90)
                hsvnormx[h][w][1]= ((hsvx[h][w][1]-128)/128)
                hsvnormx[h][w][2]= ((hsvx[h][w][2]-128)/128)
        hsvnorm[n] = hsvnormx
    return hsvnorm

This function converts the images to a single channel grayscale image

In [13]:
def GRYnorm(X):
    graynorm = np.empty([X.shape[0],image_shape[0],image_shape[1],1],dtype=float)
    for n in range(0,X.shape[0]):
        grayx = cv2.cvtColor(X[n],cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
        for h in range(0,grayx.shape[0]):
            for w in range(0,grayx.shape[1]):
                graynorm[n][h][w][0]= ((grayx[h][w]-128)/128)
    return graynorm

This function returns only the Hue channel of the HSV color space for the images.

In [14]:
def HUEnorm(X): 
    huenorm = np.empty([X.shape[0],image_shape[0],image_shape[1],1],dtype=float)
    for n in range(0,X.shape[0]):
        hsvx= cv2.cvtColor(X[n],cv2.COLOR_RGB2HSV)
        for h in range(0,hsvx.shape[0]):
            for w in range(0,hsvx.shape[1]):
                huenorm[n][h][w][0]= ((hsvx[h][w][0]-90)/90)
    return huenorm

x = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, (None, 32, 32, chan))

one_hot_y = tf.one_hot(y, 43)

The model is defined here. It is loosely based on the LeNet architecture. The comments give additional details.

In [18]:
def Model(x):    
    # Arguments used for tf.truncated_normal, 
    #randomly defines variables for the weights and biases for each layer
    mu = 0.0
    sigma = 0.1
    
    #Layer 1: Convolutional. Input = 32x32x3. Output = 28x28x18.
    #W1 size: think of the size of the kernel to pass over the image 
    #(width of filter, height of filter, input channels, output channels)
    #using tf.truncated_normal() to keep from introducing values more than two standard deviations away from mean
    W1 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape = (5, 5, chan, 18), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    #b1 size: number of output channels
    b1 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(18))
    #Set the stride for each dimension (batch_size, height, width, depth)  batch_size and depth are generally 1
    strides = [1, 1, 1, 1]
    padding = 'VALID'
    CL1 = tf.nn.conv2d(x, W1, strides, padding)
    CL1 = tf.nn.bias_add(CL1, b1)

    #Activation Function.
    AL1 = tf.nn.relu(CL1)

    #Max Pooling. Input = 28x28x18. Output = 14x14x18.
    #kernel size for max pooling filter (batch_size, height, width, depth)
    ksize = [1, 2, 2, 1]
    strides = [1, 2, 2, 1]
    padding = 'SAME'
    PL1 = tf.nn.max_pool(AL1, ksize, strides, padding)
    
    #Layer 2: Convolutional. Output = 10x10x32.
    W2 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape = (5, 5, 18, 32), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)) 
    b2 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(32))
    strides = [1, 1, 1, 1]
    padding = 'VALID'
    CL2 = tf.nn.conv2d(PL1, W2, strides, padding)
    CL2 = tf.nn.bias_add(CL2, b2)
    
    #Activation Function.
    AL2 = tf.nn.relu(CL2)
    
    #Dropout
    DL2 = tf.nn.dropout(AL2, keep_prob)
    
    #Max Pooling. Input = 10x10x32. Output = 5x5x32.
    ksize = [1, 2, 2, 1]
    strides = [1, 2, 2, 1]
    padding = 'SAME'
    PL2 = tf.nn.max_pool(DL2, ksize, strides, padding)

    #Flatten. Input = 5x5x32. Output = 800.
    FL2 = flatten(PL2)
    
    #Layer 3: Fully Connected. Input = 800. Output = 120.
    W3 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape = (800, 120), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)) 
    b3 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(120))
    CL3 = tf.matmul(FL2,W3)
    CL3 = tf.add(CL3,b3)
    
    #Activation Function.
    AL3 = tf.nn.relu(CL3)
    
    #Dropout
    DL3 = tf.nn.dropout(AL3, keep_prob)

    # Layer 4: Fully Connected. Input = 120. Output = 84.
    W4 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape = (120, 84), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    b4 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(84))
    CL4 = tf.matmul(DL3,W4)
    CL4 = tf.add(CL4,b4)
    
    
    #Activation Function.
    AL4 = tf.nn.relu(CL4)
    
    #Dropout
    DL4 = tf.nn.dropout(AL4, keep_prob)

    # Layer 5: Fully Connected. Input = 84. Output = 43.
    W5 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape = (84, 43), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    b5 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(43))
    CL5 = tf.matmul(DL4,W5)
    CL5 = tf.add(CL5,b5)
    
    logits = CL5
    
    return logits, AL1, AL2
  • Call the model
  • Compare the model results to the ground-truth labels
  • Calculate the error
  • Optimize the model's coefficients, incrementing by the learning rate
  • Minimize the error
In [19]:
#predictions for the data
logits, AL1, AL2 = Model(x)
#measures the difference between the ground-truth labels to the results of the model
cross_entropy = tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits(labels=one_hot_y, logits=logits)
#gets the average of the differences from all the training images
loss_operation = tf.reduce_mean(cross_entropy)
#minimize the loss function
optimizer = tf.train.AdamOptimizer(learning_rate = rate)
#run the minimize function on the optimizer which uses back propogation to update the network
#and minimize our training loss
training_operation = optimizer.minimize(loss_operation)

Determine the accuracy of the model predictions

In [20]:
#compare logit prediction to the one-hot encoded ground truth label
correct_prediction = tf.equal(tf.argmax(logits, 1), tf.argmax(one_hot_y, 1))
#calculate overall accuracy by averaging individual accuracies
accuracy_operation = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(correct_prediction, tf.float32))
saver = tf.train.Saver()

#batch data, run it through the model and calculates accuracy
def evaluate(X_data, y_data):
    num_examples = len(X_data)
    total_accuracy = 0
    sess = tf.get_default_session()
    for offset in range(0, num_examples, BATCH_SIZE):
        batch_x, batch_y = X_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE], y_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE]
        accuracy = sess.run(accuracy_operation, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y, keep_prob: 1.0})
        total_accuracy += (accuracy * len(batch_x))
    return total_accuracy / num_examples

Train the model.

In [21]:
with tf.Session() as sess:
    sess.run(tf.global_variables_initializer())
    num_examples = len(X_train)
    
    print("Training...")
    print()
    for i in range(EPOCHS):
        X_train, y_train = shuffle(X_train, y_train)
        for offset in range(0, num_examples, BATCH_SIZE):
            end = offset + BATCH_SIZE
            batch_x, batch_y = X_train[offset:end], y_train[offset:end]
            sess.run(training_operation, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y, keep_prob: 0.7})
            
        validation_accuracy = evaluate(X_valid, y_valid)###################
        print("EPOCH {} ...".format(i+1))
        print("Validation Accuracy = {:.3f}".format(validation_accuracy))
        print()
        
    saver.save(sess, './lenet')
    print("Model saved")

    if (predictions[i] == y_web[i]):
        countCorrect+=1
accuracy = countCorrect/predictions.shape[0]*100
print('Model accuracy on images from the web is {:.0f}%'.format(accuracy)) 

Model accuracy on images from the web is 75%

    top5Prob = sess.run(tf.nn.top_k(tf.constant(logitOutputs), k=5))

A display of this data tells us a few things. It gives us 5 sets of prediction probabilities and corresponding classes for each image. By matching the prediction probability to the class, we can see how likely the model thought that the image was of that class. A probability that is much higher than the others indicates that the model was very decisive, whereas several probabilities contending for the top spot indicates that the model could not clearly identify a correct class.

Step 4: Visualize the Neural Network's State with Test Images¶

The function below was provided in the assignment. It is used to visualize the feature maps captured at different layers of the neural network. It is interesting to see what features were picked up on by the network.

In [33]:
# image_input: the test image being fed into the network to produce the feature maps
# tf_activation: should be a tf variable name used during your training procedure that represents the calculated state of a specific weight layer
# activation_min/max: can be used to view the activation contrast in more detail, by default matplot sets min and max to the actual min and max values of the output
# plt_num: used to plot out multiple different weight feature map sets on the same block, just extend the plt number for each new feature map entry

def outputFeatureMap(image_input, tf_activation, activation_min=-1, activation_max=-1 ,plt_num=1):
    activation = tf_activation.eval(session=sess,feed_dict={x : image_input})
    featuremaps = activation.shape[3]
    plt.figure(plt_num, figsize=(15,15))
    for featuremap in range(featuremaps):
        plt.subplot(6,8, featuremap+1) # sets the number of feature maps to show on each row and column
        plt.title('FeatureMap ' + str(featuremap)) # displays the feature map number
        if activation_min != -1 & activation_max != -1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", vmin =activation_min, vmax=activation_max, cmap="gray")
        elif activation_max != -1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", vmax=activation_max, cmap="gray")
        elif activation_min !=-1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", vmin=activation_min, cmap="gray")
        else:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", cmap="gray")

I have chosen to use the Keep Left sign that I got from the web as the image to evaluate. First, I have to change shape of image from (32,32,3) to (1,32,32,3) so it will match the size of the tensor x placeholder.
